Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

         ) o

         SQL statement with SQL_ID a1j966sab7dzh.
         select max(LAST_MODIFIED_DATE) from STG_CT_CASE
   Rationale

   Rationale
      Database time for this SQL was divided as follows: 100% for SQL
      execution, 0% for parsing, 0% for PL/SQL execution and 0% for Java
      execution.
   Rationale
      SQL statement with SQL_ID "a1j966sab7dzh" was executed 1 times and had
      an average elapsed time of 87 seconds.
   Rationale
      Full scan of TABLE "FCCDW.STG_CT_CASE" with object ID 307332 consumed
      100% of the database time spent on this SQL statement.


Finding 2: Unusual "Network" Wait Event
Impact is .22 active sessions, 21.56% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Wait event "SQL*Net more data from client" in wait class "Network" was
consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .22 active sessions, 21.56% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high "SQL*Net more data from client" waits.
      Refer to Oracle's "Database Reference" for the description of this wait
      event.
   Action
      Look at the "Top SQL Statements" finding for SQL statements consuming
      significant time on the "SQL*Net more data from client" wait event. For
      example, the INSERT statement with SQL_ID "1k4q833s7vw9a" is responsible
      for 78% of these waits.

   Estimated benefit is .22 active sessions, 21.56% of total activity.

      Service "GRCCIOX".

Finding 4: Undersized PGA
Impact is .07 active sessions, 7% of total activity.
----------------------------------------------------
The PGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O to temporary
tablespaces to consume significant database time.
The value of parameter "pga_aggregate_target" was "3072 M" during the analysis
period.

   No recommendations are available.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .39 active sessions, 37.58% of total activity.


Finding 5: Undersized Redo Log Buffer
Impact is .03 active sessions, 3.22% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Waits for redo log buffer space were consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .03 active sessions, 3.22% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the redo log buffer by setting the value of
      parameter "log_buffer" to 32 M.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "log_buffer" was "7479296" during the analysis
      period.

   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .03 active sessions, 3.22% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 599 K and
      the average time per write was 10 milliseconds.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Configuration" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .03 active sessions, 3.29% of total activity.


Finding 6: Shared Pool Latches
Impact is .02 active sessions, 2.22% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Contention for latches related to the shared pool was consuming significant
database time.
Waits for "library cache lock" amounted to 2% of database time.

   No recommendations are available.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Concurrency" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .02 active sessions, 2.22% of total activity.


Finding 7: Undersized SGA
Impact is .01 active sessions, 1.33% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "5120 M" during the analysis period.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .01 active sessions, .89% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to
      5760 M.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .39 active sessions, 37.58% of total activity.
      Hard parsing of SQL statements was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .03 active sessions, 2.44% of total activity.
